.arctgz(7)            Miscellaneous Information Manual           arctgz(7)

NAME
     arctgz – safety‑first project initialisation library for the arctgz
     archive format

SYNOPSIS
     use arctgz::{init, ArctgzConfig, ArctgzError};
     use std::path::Path;

     fn init(project_path: &Path, force: bool) -> Result<(), ArctgzError>;

     struct ArctgzConfig {
         pub name:    String,
         pub version: String,
         pub include: Vec<String>,
     }

     impl ArctgzConfig {
         pub fn validate(&self) -> Result<(), ArctgzError>;
     }

     enum ArctgzError { ... }

DESCRIPTION
     The arctgz library offers a single, robust init() function that
     scaffolds a new arctgz project directory.  It enforces strict path
     confinement, validates all metadata before touching the filesystem,
     and creates the project configuration file atomically.

     init() will:
       •  create the project root directory if it does not already exist,
       •  write a default arctgz.init JSON configuration file,
       •  create an empty include/ sub‑directory.

     If the target directory already contains an arctgz.init file the
     operation fails immediately (even when force is true), preventing
     accidental overwrites of an existing project.

     All paths are resolved via std::fs::canonicalize() (realpath(3)
     semantics), so symbolic links are transparently followed during the
     home‑directory confinement check.  The library is tested on Linux,
     macOS and Windows.

INIT FUNCTION
     init(project_path, force)
             project_path
                     A reference to a std::path::Path.  Must not be
                     empty and must refer to a directory (or a non‑
                     existent location) that resides inside the user’s
                     home directory.

             force   If true, the function will proceed even when the
                     target directory is not empty, provided no
                     arctgz.init file already exists.  Existing files
                     are never overwritten.

             Returns Ok(()) on success, or an ArctgzError on failure.

TYPES
     ArctgzConfig
             Represents the contents of the arctgz.init configuration
             file.

             Fields:
               name     – project name (default "untitled").
               version  – semantic version (default "0.1.0").
               include  – list of relative resource paths (default []).

             validate()
                     Checks:
                       •  name is non‑empty, ≤ 255 chars, and contains
                          only alphanumerics, '-' or '_',
                       •  version is a valid semver string,
                       •  include paths are relative, do not contain
                          "..", and the list has at most 100 entries.
                     Returns Ok(()) or an ArctgzError::ConfigValidation.

     ArctgzError
             An enumeration covering all failure cases:

               Io(std::io::Error)
                       An I/O error occurred during directory creation
                       or file writing.

               Json(serde_json::Error)
                       JSON serialisation/deserialisation failure.

               AlreadyInitialized
                       An arctgz.init file already exists in the
                       target directory.

               InvalidPath(String)
                       The supplied path is empty, or the path exists
                       but is not a directory.

               PathNotAllowed(String)
                       The canonicalised path lies outside the user’s
                       home directory.

               DirectoryNotEmpty(String)
                       The directory exists, is not empty, and force
                       was false.

               ConfigValidation(String)
                       ArctgzConfig::validate() failed with a human‑
                       readable message.

ERRORS
     The conditions that cause init() to return each error variant are
     documented under ArctgzError above.  Callers should pattern‑match
     on the error variant to provide appropriate feedback.

EXAMPLE
     use std::path::Path;
     use arctgz;

     fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
         // scaffold a new project in ~/my-project
         let project_path = Path::new("./my-project");
         arctgz::init(project_path, false)?;
         println!("Project created successfully");
         Ok(())
     }

     After a successful run the directory looks like:

         my-project/
         ├── arctgz.init
         └── include/

     The generated arctgz.init will contain:

         {
           "name": "untitled",
           "version": "0.1.0",
           "include": []
         }

FILES
     arctgz.init
             JSON file holding project metadata.  Written atomically
             with create_new(true) – the file is never truncated or
             overwritten.

     include/
             An empty directory that serves as the default location for
             resource files that will be bundled into the final
             archive.

ENVIRONMENT
     HOME    The library obtains the home directory via the dirs crate.
             If HOME is not set it falls back to platform‑specific
             methods.  If no home directory can be determined, init()
             fails with a PathNotAllowed error for any relative path.

SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
     •  Path confinement – only paths inside the user’s home directory
        are permitted.  Symlink attacks are neutralised by
        canonicalisation before the check.
     •  Atomic config creation – the configuration file is opened with
        create_new(true), preventing TOCTOU races.
     •  Input validation – project name, version and include paths are
        validated before any filesystem modification, reducing the risk
        of injection or malformed metadata.

VERSION
     arctgz 0.1.0 – early development release.  Only project
     initialisation is implemented.  Future releases will add compile,
     verify and extract functionality.

SEE ALSO
     semver(7), realpath(3), serde_json(5), dirs(7)

BUGS
     The library is in early development.  Report issues at the project
     repository.

     The include/ directory is always created empty; there is currently
     no mechanism to add files during initialisation.  This will be
     addressed in a future release.

AUTHORS
     The arctgz developers.

